Meros 1.0 Release 

Meros is a segregated preconditioning package. It provides scalable
block preconditioning for problems that couple simultaneous solution
variables such as Navier-Strokes problems.


------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Section 1: Where you should look for Meros documentation
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In this release of Meros, the only documentation is the Doxygen documentation. 
To build a local copy of the doxygen documentation:
  $ cd Trilinos/packages/meros/doc
  $ ./build_docs

The doxygen documentation can also be found on the Meros web page:
http://software.sandia.gov/Trilinos/packages/meros/


------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Section 2: Configuring and compiling Trilinos with Meros
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

As with Trilinos in general, we suggest building Meros within a
separate Trilinos build structure. For example, Trilinos/LINUX-MPI.

Meros depends on a number of other Trilinos packages including:
teuchos, rtop, thyra, epetra, epetraext, epetra-thyra,
epetraext-thyra, aztecoo, aztecoo-thyra, ml, and ml-thyra.
 
You can find a sample configure script in Trilinos/sampleScripts.
E.g.,

  $ cd Trilinos
  $ mkdir LINUX-MPI
  $ cd LINUX-MPI
  $ ../sampleScripts/linux-meros-mpi-debug
  $ make

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Section 3: Meros examples
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Meros examples read test in matrices from files. The examples
assume that your Trilinos build directory is inside the Trilinos
directory. For example, your build directory could be
Trilinos/LINUX-BUILD. If you create your Trilinos build directory
outside Trilinos or in some other location, the examples will not run.
 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Section 4: How to submit bugs
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Bugs and enhancements should be submitted through bugzilla at the web page

   http://software.sandia.gov/bugzilla

(select Meros in the list of packages).
You will need to create a bugzilla account. Otherwise, simply e-mail
one of the developers.


------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Section 5: Mailing lists
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Users are encouraged to subscribe to the following mailing lists:

*) meros-announce@software.sandia.gov
*) meros-users@software.sandia.gov

You can subscribe to these mailing lists from Sandia's Computational
Software Site:
http://software.sandia.gov/

Select Mailman and follow the links to subscribe to specific lists.

